## Models

**The session runs on whatever model you picked** — the workflow never switches it. Two levers only:
- **Haiku subagents do mechanical, high-IO work** — `code-explorer` (reads the codebase → digest), `runner` (executes the canonical `ci.sh`/`release.sh` → pass/fail + key lines), `smoke-tester` (drives the app from prose steps → failures only). They keep bulk output off your session model; judgment stays in the main session.
- **`/consult` (best/high) for a hard call** — stuck twice, an architecture/security decision, genuinely unsure. The `reviewer` agent (best/high, fresh eyes) is the review counterpart, used sparingly for genuinely critical diffs.

## Agents — delegate proactively

Use these automatically when they fit — don't ask first. Anything that reads many files or produces bulk output belongs in a subagent.

| Agent | Use when |
|-------|----------|
| `code-explorer` (Haiku) | Any codebase question needing >3-4 files, or "where is X?" — prefer it over the built-in Explore; it reads this project's docs to orient itself |
| `runner` (Haiku) | Run the gate, a test suite, or the release script — reports pass/fail + key output, never fixes/judges |
| `smoke-tester` (Haiku) | Manually exercise a running feature from explicit prose steps (blackbox — no spec/code) — reports failing steps only |
| `reviewer` (best/high) | Fresh-eyes review of a genuinely critical diff — read-only. Default is inline self-review |

**A subagent can fail — never proceed on a missing result.** Just re-run it (the agents are idempotent — they run a script or drive the app; nothing to recover). If it fails again, ask (supervised) or write `## Blocked` (unsupervised).

## Skills — invoke proactively

**When a request matches a skill, invoke it — don't improvise a process a skill already covers.**

| User says… | Skill |
|-----------|-------|
| "capture this idea/bug" | `/draft` |
| "plan / spec out FEAT-001", "make X ready" | `/plan` |
| "implement / build FEAT-001" | `/implement` |
| "verify / does it actually work" | `/verify` |
| "commit" | `/commit` |
| "release / publish / bump version" | `/release` |
| "ship a version", "build these tickets", "work toward <topic>" | `/ship` |
| "resume / continue / I was interrupted" | `/resume` |
| "I'm stuck", a hard architecture/security call | `/consult` |
| "open a PR / submit for review" | `/pr` (optional — default merges locally) |

Multiple tasks in one message: work through them in order; in unsupervised mode apply autonomous defaults and don't stop between them. `/ship` is the built-in orchestrator for a full cycle.

## Merging

Default is **local git, no formal PR**: if the merge is fast-forward and the full gate already passed on this exact HEAD → `git merge --ff-only` (no re-run); otherwise resolve conflicts locally, re-run the full gate (`ci.sh full`), then merge. Merge commits carry `[skip ci]` unless the project is `ci-on-claude: yes`. Use `/pr` only when you want external review or the repo requires it.

## Documentation policy

Keep it minimal and useful. Doc-comments only for function usage/params, class/file usage, and genuinely tricky algorithms/decisions — not everything. Maintain one concise `docs/dev/architecture.md` (key decisions, algorithms, APIs, data model). User docs minimal — prefer self-explanatory UI + in-app hints; a little markdown for key concepts + setup.

## Session Behavior

- Session-start says `=== AUTO-RESUME REQUIRED ===` → run `/resume` immediately.
- Says `=== IN-PROGRESS WORK FOUND ===` → tell the user and suggest `/resume`; don't auto-resume.
- Says `=== BLOCKED WORK ===` → surface the blocker; don't work around it.

**State lives in the repo** — the branch, the in-progress spec's unchecked subtask boxes, and `git log`. There is no checkpoint file to maintain; `/resume` reconstructs from these. The only branch-memory notes are `## Blocked` (human needed) and `## Ship` (orchestration state).

When `unsupervised: true`: never use `AskUserQuestion` (apply the `/unsupervised` defaults); keep every subtask green-committed so an interruption loses at most the current subtask; on a genuine blocker write `## Blocked` and stop; when done, clear the notes. A usage-guard pause (local, at threshold) → finish the atomic step, commit, end the turn — you resume when usage recovers. In cloud, the recovery heartbeat resumes a rate-limit kill automatically.

## Memory

`.claude/memory/` holds project memory (decisions, gotchas, tech-debt — tracked) and runtime notes (gitignored). Read them when relevant; they're not auto-loaded.

Runtime notes: `context-{branch}.md` for a branch's `## Blocked` note — **`{branch}` = the git branch with every `/` replaced by `-`** (`feature/feat-001-x` → `context-feature-feat-001-x.md`); the hooks compute it exactly this way, so skills must too. `/ship` orchestration state lives in the **fixed, branch-independent** `context-ship.md` (a ship spans many branches).
